    ## [How do I update the Height value?](https://gsap.com/community/forums/topic/45216-how-do-i-update-the-height-value/?do=findComment&comment=220935)

    Hi,
    The main problem here resides in the fact that GSAP, for optimization reasons, stores the initial value of the property being animated to prevent constant read/write operations which could become really expensive and create performance issues. That's why you see the jump, because GSAP is actually reversing from the value the GSAP instance has, not the current value of the element's property.
    One alternative could be to create the animation on each click event. I doubt there would be a perceivable performance issue, you can even store the scroll height value of each element up front to prevent getting it each time you open an element. Like that you tell GSAP to tween the height to 0 or the scroll height value on every event, which means GSAP will use a new set of values each time. Something like this:
    https://codepen.io/GreenSock/pen/JoXpEPK
    Of course there is no collapsing of nested elements in this demo because that will require some custom logic that you already seem to have in place, but is a solid proof of concept on how to tackle this.
